<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; padding-bottom: 5px; margin-top=
: 30px; margin-bottom: 0;">Hertz</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well, <a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23822432.265382/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDUtMTIvaGVydHotcGlj=
a3Mta25pZ2h0aGVhZC1jZXJ0YXJlcy1vZmZlci1pbi1iYW5rcnVwdGN5LWF1Y3Rpb24/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cBf738f6d3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;">there it is</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">In a deal that hands a huge victory to shareholders of bankrupt Hertz G=
lobal Holdings Inc., the car renter picked Knighthead Capital Management an=
d Certares Management to buy the company out of Chapter 11, capping a drama=
tic brawl for control of the company.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The d=
eal, which gives a reorganized Hertz an enterprise value of $7.43 billion, =
was picked over an offer from a competing group led by Centerbridge Partner=
s, Warburg Pincus and Dundon Capital Partners, according to people with kno=
wledge of the matter, who asked not to be identified because the plan hasn=
=E2=80=99t been made public. The Knighthead-Certares plan would give equity=
 holders a recovery of about $8 a share -- a package that=E2=80=99s made up=
 of about $240 million in cash and warrants for nearly 20% of the reorganiz=
ed company, the people said.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Hertz shares -=
- which up until two months ago were faced with the prospects of being comp=
letely wiped out under an earlier plan -- soared as much as 41% Wednesday t=
o as high as $5.19. That approached a high of $6.25 last June, when traders=
 snapping up penny stocks on the popular Robinhood app sought to defy decad=
es of convention and make money on a bankrupt company.</p></blockquote><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That $8 number isn=E2=80=99t quite real =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0you have to decide how much you value the warrants and reorganized eq=
uity =E2=80=94=C2=A0but certainly the equity is getting something. And if y=
ou believe, or partly believe, the $8 post-bankruptcy valuation, then $6.25=
=C2=A0a year ago was a bargain. If you bought Hertz=C2=A0stock at $6.25 las=
t June, that was a reasonable bet. Not necessarily a <em>great=C2=A0</em>be=
t =E2=80=94 you=E2=80=99re down about 20% over the last year, and of course=
 you=E2=80=99d have been better off buying Dogecoin=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0but=
 a reasonable one, and=C2=A0if a few more things break=C2=A0your way you=E2=
=80=99ll have a nice little profit. And if you paid under $3 for Hertz =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0which is where it traded for=C2=A0most<em>=C2=A0</em>of last Ju=
ne =E2=80=94=C2=A0you did great.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This was, =
uh, not how it was viewed at the time. Here=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23822432.265382/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudmFuaXR=
5ZmFpci5jb20vbmV3cy8yMDIwLzA2L2JhbmtydXB0LWhlcnR6LWlzLWEtcGFuZGVtaWMtem9tYm=
ll/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1e5f584e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border=
-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: soli=
d; background-color: #ccc;">William Cohan</a>, writing last June 16, when t=
he stock closed at $1.95:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is=
 all pure gambling. There is no circumstance=E2=80=94zero=E2=80=94where Her=
tz shareholders will ever get a recovery once a plan of reorganization with=
 creditors is agreed upon, probably months from now.</p></blockquote><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">He turned out to be totally wrong =E2=80=94=C2=A0the=
 Hertz shareholders will in fact get a nice recovery =E2=80=94=C2=A0but he =
was not alone. That was pretty much what everyone thought. I hedged my bets=
 a bit, but I still indulged in making fun of the people bidding up Hertz s=
tock. I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23822432.2=
65382/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDYtM=
DkvdGhlLWJhZC1zdG9ja3MtYXJlLXRoZS1tb3N0LWZ1bg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB41d3=
485c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> wro=
te on June 9</a> about retail enthusiasm for a number of bankrupt stocks, i=
ncluding Hertz:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Corporate bankr=
uptcy doesn=E2=80=99t <em>always</em> wipe out the shareholders. If everyth=
ing really is going to get back to normal soon, then there could be enough =
money to satisfy creditors and leave shareholders with something, and clear=
ly some professional investors think that might be true about some of these=
 bankrupt names. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Analysts have pointed to improvements in ai=
r travel and used-car prices to conclude that there=E2=80=99s some chance o=
f Hertz shareholders recovering. Maybe all the companies and their creditor=
s will show up in bankruptcy court and say =E2=80=9Cnever mind, things are =
fine now, everything will go back to how it was,=E2=80=9D and the stocks wi=
ll rally. It has happened occasionally in the past=E2=80=94Bill Ackman made=
 a fortune holding General Growth Properties stock through bankruptcy=E2=80=
=94and these are strange and unprecedented times.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">On the other hand, =E2=80=9Cdebt securities tied to the companies co=
ntinue to trade below par, implying a less-than-full recovery for creditors=
 who are ranked well ahead of shareholders.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6 And it is =
=E2=80=A6 possible =E2=80=A6 that many of the thousands of brand-new invest=
ors on Robinhood have not carefully analyzed the capital structures to find=
 the fulcrum securities?</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am =
pretty embarrassed by this, because=C2=A0<em>even at the time=C2=A0</em>you=
 could pretty easily make the case for a Hertz shareholder recovery. Hertz =
blew up right at the start of the pandemic, as the mark-to-market price of =
its fleet of cars collapsed and effectively <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/23822432.265382/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvb=
S9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDUtMjYvZ29sZG1hbi13YXMtanVzdC10cnlpbmctdG8t=
aGVscA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd5e2f772" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;"> caused=C2=A0a margin call</a>=C2=A0that H=
ertz couldn=E2=80=99t meet. But the bankruptcy process grinds slowly, and e=
ven by June =E2=80=94=C2=A0a couple of weeks after it filed, which in turn =
was a few weeks after its lenders demanded more money due to the decline in=
 used-car values =E2=80=94=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/23822432.265382/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYnVzaW5lc3N3aXJlLmNvbS9uZXdzL=
2hvbWUvMjAyMDA2MTgwMDU3NjYvZW4vVXNlZC1WZWhpY2xlLU1hcmtldC1pbi1GdWxsLVJlY292=
ZXJ5/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7c47ee7a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">used-car prices</a> were recovering nicely an=
d Hertz=E2=80=99s bankruptcy looked more and more like a blip of bad timing=
. If it had made it through May and June, the story about Hertz might have =
been =E2=80=9CHertz is doing surprisingly well, sure travel is down but not=
 as much as expected, and it=E2=80=99s had a weird windfall from rising use=
d-car prices.=E2=80=9D Avis Budget Group, another big rental-car company, h=
ad a rough few months in early 2020 but was doing better by mid-June; by Ma=
rch 2021 its stock was at all-time highs. Without the disruption of bankrup=
tcy,=C2=A0wouldn=E2=80=99t Hertz=E2=80=99s valuation have had roughly the s=
ame trajectory?=C2=A0<em>With=C2=A0</em>the disruption of bankruptcy, shoul=
dn=E2=80=99t the stock still be worth something?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">The nice thing about stock markets is that everyone gets to decide fo=
r themselves: If you think that Hertz is undervalued and will recover, you =
can buy the stock; if you think that anyone buying Hertz is crazy, you can =
just not buy it. The stock price will reflect some aggregate of people=E2=
=80=99s expectations; in June 2020, you or I might have said that those exp=
ectations were crazy, but they turned out to be pretty accurate.</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One lesson here is that I know nothing and nothing in=
 this column is ever investing advice. An important lesson!</p><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">Another lesson is that the conventional wisdom that, when =
debt and equity prices conflict,=C2=A0distressed-debt investors are smart a=
nd understand valuation and fulcrum securities, while equity investors are =
dumb retail gamblers who know nothing and buy stock for fun, might be wrong=
? There is a temperamental difference between equity investors and distress=
ed credit investors: Distressed investors think about the downside and what=
 might go wrong; equity investors think about the upside and what might go =
right. In the spring of 2020, in the dark days of a global pandemic, it see=
med smart to focus on the downside. But in fact=C2=A0the stock market<em>=
=C2=A0</em>was back at all-time highs by September, and if you bet on the w=
orst stocks in May your optimism was rewarded.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">But the other thing to remember about Hertz is that Hertz, looking at a=
ll these enthusiastic buyers of its stock, decided to do something about it=
. It <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23822432.2653=
82/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDYtMTIv=
aWYteW91LXdhbnQtaGVydHotaGF2ZS1zb21lLWhlcnR6/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7e133=
872" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> deci=
ded to sell them stock</a>. To raise money, to fund its business and pay of=
f its creditors and maybe emerge from bankruptcy with some value intact.=C2=
=A0It warned investors that, by any conventional standards, they were being=
 foolish; <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23822432=
.265382/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDY=
tMjIvdGhlLWJlc3QtZnJhdWQtaXMtaW4tcGxhaW4tc2lnaHQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd=
5cbc316" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #00=
0000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bo=
ttom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> =
its prospectus said</a> =E2=80=9Cwe expect that common stock holders would =
not receive a recovery through any plan=E2=80=9D unless there was=C2=A0=E2=
=80=9Ca significant and rapid and currently unanticipated improvement in bu=
siness conditions to pre-COVID-19 or close to pre-COVID-19 levels.=E2=80=9D=
 And then there was a significant and rapid improvement in conditions, and =
the shareholders did get a recovery.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But be=
fore Hertz could sell much stock, the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commissi=
on <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23822432.265382=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDYtMjIvdG=
hlLWJlc3QtZnJhdWQtaXMtaW4tcGxhaW4tc2lnaHQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCd5cbc316=
" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> shut do=
wn the offering</a>. It never really said why. Well, <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23822432.265382/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21i=
ZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDYtMTcvaGVydHotc3VzcGVuZHMtcGxhbi10by1=
zZWxsLXdvcnRobGVzcy1zdG9jay1hZnRlci1zZWMtc2NydXRpbnk/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cB80b790ff" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;"> there was this</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=
=9CWe have let the company know that we have comments on their disclosure,=
=E2=80=9D SEC Chairman Jay Clayton said in a CNBC interview Wednesday. =E2=
=80=9CIn most cases when you let a company know that the SEC has comments o=
n their disclosure, they do not go forward until those comments are resolve=
d.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it=E2=80=99s n=
ot clear what the comments were, and, again, it=E2=80=99s not like Hertz di=
dn=E2=80=99t warn investors that it was bankrupt and their investment would=
 probably be worthless. It was =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/23822432.265382/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZ=
XdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDYtMTgvaGVydHotc2hhcmVzLWhhbHRlZC1hbWlkLXJldGhpbmtp=
bmctb2Ytc3RvY2stc2FsZS1pbi1iYW5rcnVwdGN5/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB04681721"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> fraud in=
 plain sight</a>,=E2=80=9D as one lawyer called it. The problem surely was =
not=C2=A0<em>disclosure</em>; it was that the SEC thought =E2=80=94=C2=A0as=
 I thought, and William Cohan thought, and everyone thought =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
the investors were throwing away their money, and it seemed wrong to let He=
rtz take that money.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But we were all wrong!=
 They were right! If they had been able to give Hertz their money, Hertz mi=
ght have exited bankruptcy more quickly and efficiently and preserved more =
value, and those shareholders would have made money. The people who=C2=A0<e=
m>did=C2=A0</em>buy in the offering, before the SEC shut it down, <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/23822432.265382/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDgtMTEvZ29sZG1hbi1s=
b3Zlcy1hLWdvb2QtY3Jpc2lz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0a9309f6" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: n=
one !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bor=
der-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> paid about $2.08 per sha=
re</a>, meaning that they are sitting on more than a 100% profit over about=
 11 months. More investors could have gotten that deal, but the SEC said no=
.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The core=C2=A0idea of U.S. securities law=
 is disclosure: Companies should accurately and completely disclose their s=
ituations to investors, and then investors get to make up their own minds a=
bout what stocks to buy and how much to pay. In weird and bubbly and meme-y=
 times, that idea makes people nervous: =E2=80=9CSure sure sure you have di=
sclosed all your financial information, but you are=C2=A0<em>bankrupt</em>,=
 how can you sell stock to people? How can they buy it?=E2=80=9D And so the=
re is a temptation to meddle, to restrict trades even with full disclosure,=
 to protect investors from their own fully informed but apparently crazy=C2=
=A0decisions. With Hertz, that happens to have been a mistake.</p><h2 style=
=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial, Helveti=
ca, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; padding-bottom: 5px; margin-top: 30px; m=
argin-bottom: 0;">SEC vs. Bitcoin</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I think =
it is fair to say that the institutional financial industry is really excit=
ed about absorbing and domesticating Bitcoin. Bitcoin is some weird thing t=
hat lives on a blockchain, but if you are a big institutional investor you =
can, increasingly, access it in normal traditional ways. You can buy cash-s=
ettled=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/238224=
32.265382/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTctM=
TItMTkvYml0Y29pbi1mdXR1cmVzLWFyZS1hLWdyZWF0LXdheS10by1ub3Qtb3duLWJpdGNvaW4/=
